    <name>
				<text>(not in quiz, copy with c,d) 37.2.3.12 A service engineer can be called</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p><p>A service engineer can be called out for maintenance on the photocopiers in the offices of four large companies, A, B, C and D. On any given week there is a probability of {@p@} that he will be called to each of these companies. The event of being called to one company is independent of whether or not he is called to any of the others.</p><p>Find the probability that, on a particular day:</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">

<li><p>he is called to all four companies: [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p></li>

<li><p>he is called to at least three companies: [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p></li>

<li><p>he is called to all four given that he is called to at least one: [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p></li>

<li><p> he is called to all four given that he is called to Company A: [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</p></li>

</ol>

<p>Finally, find the expected value:&nbsp;[[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]] and variance:&nbsp;[[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] [[feedback:prt6]] of the number of these companies which call the engineer on a given day.</p><p><b>Note</b>: please round your answers up to 4 decimal places.</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p><b>SOLUTION:</b></p><p>Let \( Y \) be the number of companies to which the engineer is called and let \( A \) denote the event that the engineer is called to company A.</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">

<li><p>\(\text{P}(Y=4) = {@p@}^{4} = {@ta_1@} \)</p></li>

<li><p>\(\text{P}(Y \geq 3) = \left( \begin{array}{c} 4 \\ 3 \end{array} \right) \times  {@p@}^{3} \times {@1 - p@}^{1} + {@p@}^{4} = {@ta_2@} \)</p></li>

<li><p>\( \begin{align} \text{P}(Y=4 \mid Y \geq 1) &amp;= \dfrac{\text{P}(Y=4 \cap Y \geq 1)}{\text{P}(Y \geq 1)} = \dfrac{\text{P}(Y=4)}{ 1 - \text{P}(Y &lt; 1)} \\ &amp; = \dfrac{{@ta_1@}}{1-{@1 - p@}^4} = \dfrac{{@ta_1@}}{{@1 - ((1-p)^4)@}}  = {@ta_3@}. \end{align} \)</p></li>

<li><p>\( \text{P}(Y=4 \mid A)= \dfrac{\text{P}(Y=4 \cap A)}{\text{P}(A)} = \dfrac{\text{P}(Y=4)}{\text{P}(A)} = \frac{{@ta_1@}}{{@p@}} = {@ta_4@}. \)</p></li>

</ol>

<p>Finally, if you remember the formulas given in a previous Key point, the mean is \( \text{E}(Y) = np = 4 \times {@p@} = {@ta_5@}. \) The variance is \( V(Y) = np(1-p) = 4 \times {@p@} \times {@1-p@} = {@ta_6@} \)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
